WEBVTT

NOTE Captions for "Merkle trees and append-only logs" (Topic 7). No audio track
NOTE yet by decision; these captions carry the narration. Source of truth:
NOTE learn/manim/scripts/merkle-trees.md

00:00.000 --> 00:12.000
Say we publish a list — every key we've ever issued — and promise we'll only ever add to it. Never edit. Never delete. How would you catch us if we broke that?

00:12.000 --> 00:24.000
You could download the whole list every day and compare. But it grows forever, and it only works if you never miss a day.

00:24.000 --> 00:40.000
Here's the real answer. Hash each entry. Take those fingerprints in pairs, and hash each pair together. Half as many. Do it again. And again.

00:40.000 --> 00:52.000
Until there's one left — the root. This is the actual root of one of our live logs, right now: sixty entries, one fingerprint.

00:52.000 --> 01:12.000
Watch what happens if we change one character in one entry. Its fingerprint changes, which changes its parent's, which changes the next one up — and the root is completely different.

01:12.000 --> 01:26.000
There's no way to edit an entry and keep the root the same. That would mean two different things with the same fingerprint — the exact thing these functions prevent.

01:26.000 --> 01:44.000
So the root is a fingerprint of the entire list, in sixty-four characters. You don't download fifty thousand entries to check we've been honest — you compare sixty-four characters.

01:44.000 --> 02:04.000
Now the honest limit. A Merkle tree doesn't stop us writing something false. Add a dishonest entry, and the tree would include it quite happily.

02:04.000 --> 02:22.000
What it takes away is our ability to lie quietly. We can't show you one list and someone else a different one. We can't change our story later. Everyone comparing roots gets the same answer.

02:22.000 --> 02:30.000
That's a smaller claim than "trust us to be honest." It's also a much better one — because you don't have to. Try it below: change any entry, and watch the root move.
